The tarte was well balanced and the bread pudding savory (quite large-xtra to take home). Coffee was a bitter roast. Was okay but thought things would be better

Context: My friends and I (total of 4) went in on Saturday of Labor Day weekend around 6 pm. I rank each category (parking, service, food, pricing, etc) between 1-5 stars each and then take the average for the overall! 1) Parking: I don't recommend driving, bus it if you can. Parking is a hassle almost everywhere in SF. Take the bus and walk around to Bi-Rite then Fayes and saunter about...it will make you feel better about the gluttony that's about to ensue! *** 2) Wait: The line actually was not that long. Approximately 15-20 minutes. Bring some friends, good conversation always makes waiting in line better! Also, you each can get something different and try each other's in order to try more things! *** 3) Seating is very very limited. But that's SF for you! Lots of people swarming in a line right up against the tables is uncomfortable. If the table was empty, it was in dire need of a good bussing. You would have to bus two parties' worth of plates yourself in order to sit at that table. Its super busy, we understand. So we sat outside. It was fine because it had more space, less cramped, and fresh air. *** But if you don't read anymore. Please read the story at the end of the food section! Skip to it now if you're feeling lazy! 4) The most important item of business: FOOD! Keepin' It Real: We are all here for that damn banana cream pie! I know it, Yelp knows it, and Tartine knows it. So if we all know that we all want banana cream p, why would you ever run out? I understand it was 6 and you close at 8, but your line is always long! So justify the line by providing the product we demand. I really wish I didn't have to do this, but I have to give you only *** for pricing and product availability. You also ran out of morning buns...boo! Each item we tried was $5-7 which is entering the higher price ranges of overall pastry places. So what did we order then?! Coffee: Refill your mug yourself! So essentially unlimited refills! But please be reasonable, don't be that person that is constantly refilling coffee and hogging a table! It was delicious even black, so you know it's good stuff! ***** Lemon cream tart: We ordered this to compensate for lack of banana cream. Great, strong, natural lemon flavor, very smooth! Unexpectedly good banana cream substitute! ****1/2 Frangipane tart: It was pretty good, except it was best with the coffee! The crust was very flaky and good balance of fruit, cruit, and almonds. But, I couldn't have finished it by itself. Definitely needs the coffee. **** Bread pudding: Nice effort Tartine. But I've tasted better. The most disappointing dish of the three we had, but all of them were good so its compared to a high standard. The texture was one dimensionally mushy, like jello. I couldn't taste the fruit. It was decent, I just had high expectations due to yelp recommendations. That's hype for you! But, it makes up for itself! *** HERE'S THE STORY: The best part about the bread pudding was that a stranger who looked homeless walked down the street towards our table. He stopped, leaned over, and looked like he was about to ask for change and suddenly, THIS MAN JUST DIPPED HIS HAND INTO OUR HALF EATEN PUDDING, SCOOPED IT UP, STUCK IT IN HIS MOUTH, THREW WHAT WAS LEFT IN HIS HAND ON THE FLOOR AND TABLE, THEN SPAT SOME OUT ON THE STREET, LEAVING A TRAIL OF SAD, MUSHED UP UNAPPRECIATED BREAD PUDDING... Appalling, unexpected, and just surreal. It all happened so fast! Of course this is unacceptable. If you're going to take the food at least savor it, man! I am sorry, but this should not be happening to customers. But, its not Tartine's fault...We told the servers and what did they say? They apologized kindly telling us that this has happened before and that they have called the police on him multiple times already and then...they gave us two chocolate puddings! 5 star response! Bravo, Tartine! I will make it 6 stars because they gave not just one, but two chocolate puddings! So in the addendum to this review is the chocolate pudding! Chocolate pudding: Delicious! It was rich with a deep rich chocolate flavor. The cream and chocolate shavings on top added a nice change in texture. But, it probably tasted even better because it was a free consolation prize! ****1/2 Rankings: *** no parking, but great waking area *** cramped seating/plate piling up on tables *** price and availability, no banana cream! ***** great coffee! ****1/2 flavorful lemon cream tart **** frangipane paired with coffee *** average bread pudding ****** service! ****1/2 consolatory chocolate puddings! Tartine sits comfortably in an exclusive class of American bakeries that help set the standard for amazing pastries and other baked goodies. There's almost always a line regardless of what time of day you go, but I've never had to wait more than 30 minutes. During this time, you can breathe in the scent of freshly baked pastries waft from the door while you catch up with friends - honestly not too shabby. Everyone has their favorites so it's hard to say you MUST try something for fear of you having to miss out on trying your favorite pastry. I WILL say that my favorites are the croissants (regular or ham and cheese) and the banana cream pie. Both are stellar. I wasn't thrilled with the honey bun or the bread pudding (but still good), but my friends absolutely loved these. I'm hard pressed to think of many other bakeries I've been too where I can say that with a completely straight face. The bakery is as cute as a button and just about the size of a button. There are a handful of tables inside and another half a dozen tables outside. This is not the place to come with your tour group - probably best to take everyone's order in advance. And remember, just keep your patience as you make your way through the line. Half the pleasure seems to be in the wait for that first bite.

Creating those huge croissants and other pastries make them 1. more expensive (on purpose?) 2. too much food (way more than one person would need) and 3. messes with the proportions. I happened to be in Mission this morning around their opening time (7:30 am), so seized this opportunity to go there to experience first hand their freshly baked croissants. When I got there about 7:40 am the line just barely started to form so I was able to get in right away. Lucky me! There were a few foreigners before me that are apparently visitors here as they were speaking in some European language. And people were taking photos of their pastries just like what I was doing. That's more proof on how famous Tartine is. I've had their almond croissants before so opted to try their original flavor croissant and a morning bun. The croissant is huge and costs $3.95 each. Same price is a morning bun, which is slightly smaller than the croissant. I also got a buttermilk currant scone at $3.25 each and an almond rocher at only 85 cents each. While there were a lot of seatings still available at the time, I opted to take the goodies home with me as I had to go back to Foster City to work. There was literally no traffic at the time on 101 so I got home a little after 8 am. Since there was no time to waste before going to work, I quickly devoured half the croissant and the entire morning bun. (Note I meant to only have one bite of each, but as usual for pastries this caliber there is just no way to fight it no matter how disciplined you are). So I only have one word for both the croissant and the morning bun: ORGASMIC! The best I have tasted so far. People don't wait in long lines all day long there for nothing. I managed to take only two bites out of the buttermilk currant scone and then saved the rest of it and the half remaining croissant in the freezer for another day, as carb loading is usually not my way of starting the day; but then hey it's Friday so I can cut myself some slack...Anyway back to the buttermilk currant scone: it's also the BEST buttermilk scone I've ever had. Good thing no one was around me when I took the first bite as I was moaning and felt like there was a "party in my mouth".... Later in the day I also tried the almond rocher. For 85 cents the size is quite large, compared to the now popular French macarons, which are usually priced at $2 each and way much smaller than this, this is a steal. It's very sugary as all meringue type of pastries are, but the chopped almond pieces in it sort of balances out the sweetness to give a nutty flavor as well as the crunchy texture. It reminds me of the Chinese hua sheng tung (penut brittle candy) that I used to eat in Taiwan as a child, only it's more chewy due to the meringue. Since everything I've tasted is so so good, I decided to get on Amazon to get their first cookbook to hopefully learn a trick or two on how to make these decadent classic pastries myself, some day. For now, I'll just need to plan on another trip to go back soon to taste other items such as quiche, banana cream pie or the open faced grilled cheese sandwich.

    The bakery is as cute as a button and just about the size of a button. Â There are a handful of tables inside and another half a dozen tables outside.     The pastries were good, but were "Americanized". They were just too big. There is a reason why French came up with the perfect size... it's enough for one person, it includes just the right amount so that it won't be too wet or too dry. Creating those huge croissants and other pastries make them 1. more expensive (on purpose?) 2. too much food (way more than one person would need) and 3. messes with the proportions. For example, the eclairs had too much filling with messes with the perfect ratio of a properly made eclair.
    In closing, good for American taste, but ok for anyone who's had the real thing, and knows what to expect.

The morning bun was amazing as well. Not to sweet and crunchy on the outside. I love morning buns for breakfast. Wish they have a Tartine Bakery near me. I order a latte as well. Coffee is best with pastries. The guy who made my latte was amazing and he was so nice.

    Since we waited for an hour, we decided to get everything. We also got the mushroom Croque Monsieur. We also wanted the ham Croque Monsieur but was sold out so we got the turkey instead. The mushroom Croque Monsieur was AMAZING. Delicious!! The turkey was just okay. Nothing special.

    With just the two of us, we wanted to try everything but wouldn't be able to eat it all at one sitting, therefore we got a bag of goodies to go. We got the banana cream pie. SO GOOD. it was not too sweet and the texture of the banana cream was so light and smooth. We also got the lemon tart. Not too tart and just the right amount of sweetness. On the other hand, the lemon bar was too tart for me. Didn't like it as much. The last item I got was their almond lemon tea bar. It was so yummy! Better than any of the breakfast cakes I ever had.

    My over experience was great. The wait was longer than I hope but I left tartine happy. My taste buds and tummy was satisfied.     4 check-ins

    I happened to be in Mission this morning around their opening time (7:30 am), so seized this opportunity to go there to experience first hand their freshly baked croissants. When I got there about 7:40 am the line just barely started to form so I was able to get in right away. Lucky me! There were a few foreigners before me that are apparently visitors here as they were speaking in some European language. And people were taking photos of their pastries just like what I was doing. That's more proof on how famous Tartine is. I've had their almond croissants before so opted to try their original flavor croissant and a morning bun. The croissant is huge and costs $3.95 each. Same price is a morning bun, which is slightly smaller than the croissant. I also got a buttermilk currant scone at $3.25 each and an almond rocher at only 85 cents each.

    While there were a lot of seatings still available at the time, I opted to take the goodies home with me as I had to go back to Foster City to work. There was literally no traffic at the time on 101 so I got home a little after 8 am.

    Since there was no time to waste before going to work, I quickly devoured half the croissant and the entire morning bun. (Note I meant to only have one bite of each, but as usual for pastries this caliber there is just no way to fight it no matter how disciplined you are). So I only have one word for both the croissant and the morning bun:

    ORGASMIC!

    The best I have tasted so far. People don't wait in long lines all day long there for nothing.

    I managed to take only two bites out of the buttermilk currant scone and then saved the rest of it and the half remaining croissant in the freezer for another day, as carb loading is usually not my way of starting the day; but then hey it's Friday so I can cut myself some slack...Anyway back to the buttermilk currant scone: it's also the BEST buttermilk scone I've ever had. Good thing no one was around me when I took the first bite as I was moaning and felt like there was a "party in my mouth"....

    Later in the day I also tried the almond rocher. For 85 cents the size is quite large, compared to the now popular French macarons, which are usually priced at $2 each and way much smaller than this, this is a steal. It's very sugary as all meringue type of pastries are, but the chopped almond pieces in it sort of balances out the sweetness to give a nutty flavor as well as the crunchy texture. It reminds me of the Chinese hua sheng tung (penut brittle candy) that I used to eat in Taiwan as a child, only it's more chewy due to the meringue.

    Since everything I've tasted is so so good, I decided to get on Amazon to get their first cookbook to hopefully learn a trick or two on how to make these decadent classic pastries myself, some day.

    For now, I'll just need to plan on another trip to go back soon to taste other items such as quiche, banana cream pie or the open faced grilled cheese sandwich.
